1. Main Concepts¶

Astronomical Applications:¶

  • Detection of variability and periodicity
  • Treatment of nonperiodic variability
  • Searches for localized events

Exoplanet Searches, Variable Stars, Supernovae, Active Galactic Nuclei, Gamma Ray Bursts, Gravitational Wave Events, etc.

Variables: $(t_{1},y_{1}), ... , (t_{n},y_{n})$

  • Similar to regression analysis (replace $t$ with $x$), except each $y$ depends on the previous value of $y$

Main Tasks:¶

  1. Characterize the correlation and significance between different values of $y$
  2. Predict future values of $y$

Types of Variability:¶

  1. Periodic -- regular and predicatable such as RR Lyrae and Cepheid Variables
  2. Stochastic -- changes are always there but are not predictiable for an indefinite period such as AGN
  3. Localized -- bursts such as solar flares, supernovae, GRBs, gravitational wave events

(will be discussed in greater detail in the following two lectures)

2. Modeling Toolkits¶

Main set of toolkits either belong to the time or frequency domain

Time Domain:

  • Signal Detection: Parameter Estimation, Regression, Classification Methods
  • Modeling: Bayesian Model odds ratio, AIC criteria, BIC criteria

Frequency Domain:

  • Fourier Analysis
  • Discrete Fourier Transforms
  • Wavelet Analysis
  • Digital Filtering

2.1 Fourier Analysis¶

Definitions

In words: general, complicated functions are representated/approximated by integrals/sums of simpler trigonometric functions

Mathematical Definition for function $h(t)$:

Fourier Transform:

$H(f) = \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} h(t)e^{(-i2\pi ft)}\mathrm{d}t$

Inverse Fourier Transform:

$h(t) = \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} H(f)e^{(i2\pi ft)}\mathrm{d}f$

Work really well with periodic time series data

Example: RR Lyrae Light Curve

Convolution Theorem (Smoothing):

A convolution of two functions $a(t)$ and $b(t)$ is given by

$(a*b)(t) = \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} a(t')b(t-t')\mathrm{d}t'$

Astronomical Implication:

  • Ground-based imaging convolves the true intensity distribution on the sky with atmospheric seeing (equavalent to diffraction patterns in space); ie. resolution is never infinite

Fourier Transform Application:

If $h = a*b$ then the Fourier Transforms are all related by their pointwise products:

$H(f) = A(f)B(f)$

To obtain original signal, $b$, take the inverse Fourier transform of the ratio $H(f)/A(f)$

Note: Choose the function you use to convolve your data wisely

Discrete Fourier Transform

  • Data is always directly sampled -- need a way to transform previously defined Fourier Transforms into discrete applications
  • When binned, such as when using CCDs, our h(t) function becomes sampled at N equal intervals such that $h_j = h(t_j)$; $t_j = t_0 +j\Delta t$, $j = 0, ... , (N-1)$

Discrete Fourier Transform:

$H_k = \sum_{j=0}^{N-1} h_je^{(-i2\pi jk / N)}$

Discrete Inverse Fourier Transform:

$h_j = \frac{1}{N}\sum_{k=0}^{N-1} H_ke^{(i2\pi jk / N)}$

where $k = 0, ... , (N-1)$

Fast Fourier Transform (FFT)

Definition: Algorithm for computing discrete Fourier Transforms in $\mathcal O(N\mathrm{log}N)$ time rather than $\mathcal O(N^2)$

Astronomical Implication: Due to its much faster speed than traditional discrete Fourier Transforms it's widely used with analyzing evenly sampled, high signal-to-noise ratio, time series data such as LIGO data

Common FFT Method: Welch's Method -- computes multiple Fourier Transforms over overlapping windows of the data to smooth noise effects in the resulting spectrum as seen in LIGO example

2.2 Wavelets¶

  • Fourier Transforms don't work well with nonperiodic time series analysis (especially bursts) since they're based in infinite trigonometric functions
  • Could evaluate Fourier Transforms in short bursts but this breaks down with degraded spectral resolution and is biased depending on the choice of time series segmentation length
  • Wavelets present one way to handle nonperiodic time series analysis

Definition: basis functions that are localized in both frequency and time domains

$w(t|t_0, f_0, Q) = A e^{(i2\pi f_0(t-t_0))}e^{(-f_0^2(t-t_0)^2/Q^2)}$

where $t_0$ is the central time, $f_0$ is the central frequency, and $Q$ (dimensionless) is a model parameter which controls the width of the frequency window

Wavelet Transform:

$H_w(t_0;f_0,Q) = \int_{-\infty}^{\infty}h(t)w(t|t_0, f_0,Q)$

**Note:** By the true mathematical definition of wavelets this equation is actually off by a scaling factor; however, the textbook uses it to focus on the main goal when using wavelets -- localization in time and frequency

2.3 Digital Filtering¶

Goal: reduce noise or compress time series data

Examples:

  • Low Pass Filtering: suppress high frequencies
  • High Pass Filtering: suppress low frequencies
  • Passband Filtering: finite range of frequencies admitted
  • Notch Filtering: finite range of frequencies is blocked

Fourier and wavelet analysis can be used as filtering techniques

Main Caveat: always decreases the information/content of data

  • Can be biased in a similar way as binning data with histograms

Low Pass Filtering¶

Two Examples:

  1. Wiener Filtering: uses Fourier techniques but will only work for evenly sampled data
  2. Savitzky-Golay Filtering: fits low-order polynomials by using sliding windows

Note: These methods do not set the frequency space you want to exclude as zero since that can produce "ringing" or unwanted osciallations in the signal

High Pass Filtering¶

  • Only one example, baseline estimate in spectral data, which has no universally accepted/defined function
  • First step toward estimating model parameters of spectral lines (location, width, strength)

Minimum Component Filtering:

  1. Determine which regions to exclude and fit a baseline model (like a polynomial) to the rest of the data
  2. Apply discrete Fourier transform
  3. Remove high frequencies using a low-pass filter and apply an inverse Fourier transform to the result
  4. Add the baseline fit that was previously subtracted to the result from the inverse Fourier transform

3. Summary¶

Main Tasks for Time Series Analysis:¶

  1. Characterize the correlation and significance between different values of $y$
  2. Predict future values of $y$

Main Set of Toolkits:¶

Time Domain:

  • Signal Detection: Parameter Estimation, Regression, Classification Methods
  • Modeling: Bayesian Model odds ratio, AIC criteria, BIC criteria

Frequency Domain:

  • Fourier Analysis (periodic)
  • Discrete Fourier Transforms (periodic)
  • Wavelet Analysis (nonperiodic)
  • Digital Filtering (way of applying Fourier and Wavelet analysis to reduce noise)

Next two lectures will go into more detail regarding the types of variability and how to apply these toolkits to specific examples

4. Research Application:¶

Quasars¶

  • Most luminous type of AGN -- among the most luminous objects in the universe
  • Basic Structure -- accretion disk surrounding a Supermassive Black Hole at the center of galaxies which produces ionizing radiation
  • Inner Regions -- accretion disk, dust torus, and broad emission line region all directly affected by the SMBH but on scales that can't be spatially resolved (sub-parsec scales for $10^8 M_\odot$ SMBH)

Time series analysis can provide observational constraints on these regions that can't be spatially resolved

Reverberation Mapping¶

  • Determines the characteristic size of broad emission line regions by measuring the time delay of the broad-line regions in quasar spectra as the mean light-travel time across the broad-line region

ref. 2

Reverberation Mapping Results and Importance¶

Results:

  • Estimate SMBH masses by combining this characteristic size with the velocity dispersion of the broad-line emission regions (determined from the width of the broad-line regions)
  • Can determine more detailed structure/kinematics of the broad-line region through modeling methods

Importance:

  • Better study accretion processes and how feedback can effect the host galaxies and surrounding circumgalactic medium
  • Better constrain possible coevolution between SMBHs and their host galaxies
  • Understanding SMBHs throughout various epochs

Changing-Look Quasars:¶

  • Show slow, consistent photometric and spectral variability over many years -- emerging/disappearing broad-line regions
    ref. 3

Changing-Look Quasars and Problems with Current Theory¶

  • Shows changes over time in accretion rate/flow
  • Presents problems for the current unified model of AGN and the Standard Accretion Disk Theory

Unified Model of AGN:

  • Explains that the characteristics separating different classes/types of AGN are due to the geometry of the SMBH's surroundings
  • Changing-Look Quasars challenge this since its intrinsic geometry relative to the observer shouldn't change

Standard Accretion Disk Theory:

  • Observed timescale of these changes is much shorter than what is currently required by the standard accretion disk theory to significantly change the accretion rate
  • Highlighted since these changes are taking place in only a few years when considered from the quasar rest frame

Future with Changing-Look Quasars¶

  • New way to study accretion disk structure and environments
  • Can probe changes in quasar continuum emission
  • New way to study the stucture of broad-line regions
  • Current (SDSS) and future (LSST) surveys will continue to find more of these objects

SMBH Binaries¶

  • Expected result from hierarchical galaxy formation models
  • Predicted main source of nanofrequency gravitational waves
  • Changes in the light curves of these candidates are consistent with binary motion (Graham et al. 2015a, b)

ref. 3

SMBH Binaries¶

Physical mechanisms for the periodicity aren't easily identifiable:

  1. Jet Precession
  2. Warped Accretion Disks
  3. Relativistic Doppler Boosting
  4. Periodic Accretion

All methods listed imply a binary system and aren't easily accountable with single SMBH models

Reserach Summary¶

Time series analysis can provide observational constraints on regions near the SMBH of quasars that can't be spatially resolved

  1. Reverberation Mapping
  2. Changing-Look Quasars
  3. SMBH Binaries

Allows for better studies regarding SMBHs, galaxy evolution, coevolution of galaxies and their SMBHs, how accreting SMBHs affect the circumgalactic medium
